{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\nFor high assurance, a developer routes the gate to a trusted rebar-mcp server that runs the\nverifier and signs. Integrity requires the server to fetch authoritative state itself (never client\ninputs). Includes the AWS deployment (IaC declaration; actual provisioning is operator work).\n\n**Transport (the existing rebar-mcp is stdio-only).** The shipped `rebar-mcp` server runs FastMCP\nover **stdio** and is not network-exposed. The trusted remote path is therefore a **library-mode\nHTTP service** — rebar imported as a library behind a thin HTTP handler, mirroring the proven\n`review_bot` pattern (no stdio-MCP transport work) — fronted by **AWS API Gateway**, which is the\nSigV4 integration point. The default local path is unchanged: the offline stdio `rebar-mcp`.\n\n**AWS infra decisions (from the epic's design resolution).** The signing key is **Ed25519**, signed\nvia **SSHSIG** by the server itself — NOT AWS KMS managed signing (AWS KMS asymmetric SIGN_VERIFY\nsupports only ECDSA/RSA, not Ed25519). Concretely:\n- **Signing key storage + materialization.** The Ed25519 private key material lives in **AWS\n  Secrets Manager**, encrypted at rest by a **KMS CMK**. The shipped `sshsig.sign(pae, key_path,\n  namespace)` invokes `ssh-keygen -Y sign -f <key_path>` and so requires a **file path**, not raw\n  bytes. Resolution: at signing time the server fetches the secret and **materializes it to a\n  0600-mode temp file** (`mkstemp`), passes that path to `signing.sign_opcert_manifest` /\n  `sshsig.sign`, and **deletes it in a `finally`** (never persisted to disk beyond the signing\n  call). No change to `sshsig.sign`'s signature is needed. \"KMS\" is envelope-encryption of the\n  secret at rest, not the signing operation.\n- **Endpoint authentication:** **AWS IAM (SigV4-signed requests) restricted to a named admin\n  role**, over TLS. (This is the human/admin authentication requirement.)\n- **Least-privilege IAM:** the server's execution role may read only the one signing secret + the\n  repo (review remote) at the requested commit; nothing else.\n\n**Compute environment (ssh-keygen ≥ 8.9).** SSHSIG signing shells out to `ssh-keygen -Y sign` and\n`sshsig.ensure_available()` hard-requires OpenSSH ≥ 8.9. The trusted server therefore runs as a\n**container image** (a Lambda *container image* or ECS/Fargate task, fronted by API Gateway) whose\nDockerfile installs **OpenSSH ≥ 8.9** — NOT a bare managed Lambda runtime (whose image may lack a\nrecent ssh-keygen). The IaC test asserts the Dockerfile/image installs OpenSSH.\n\n**HTTP handler contract.** The handler accepts ONLY identifiers, never trustable state:\n- Request (JSON): `{\"ticket_id\": str, \"kind\": \"completion-verifier\"|\"plan-review\", \"commit\": str}`\n  (the gate to run + the `main` commit to bind). Any extra client-supplied fields (e.g. a\n  `material_fingerprint`) are IGNORED.\n- The handler fetches the authoritative ticket state (tickets branch) + code at `commit` (review\n  remote), runs the gate, computes the material fingerprint ITSELF, and signs an op-cert via\n  `signing.sign_opcert_manifest`.\n- Response (JSON): `{\"verdict\": \"PASS\"|\"FAIL\", \"envelope\": <encoded DSSE>|null,\n  \"material_fingerprint\": str, \"merged_log_commit\": str}` — the bound values are the\n  authoritative ones the server computed.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The trusted server is a library-mode HTTP service (rebar-as-library behind a thin HTTP\n      handler, per the review_bot pattern — NOT the stdio rebar-mcp) fronted by AWS API Gateway,\n      accepting the request schema above and returning the response schema above (test on the\n      request/response round-trip against a fake authoritative source).\n- [ ] The handler fetches ticket state + code-at-commit from authoritative remotes ITSELF and runs\n      the gate on that, ignoring client-provided state. Concrete integrity test: the handler is\n      invoked with a **doctored `material_fingerprint`** (not matching the ticket's authoritative\n      material); it recomputes the fingerprint from the fetched authoritative ticket and signs the\n      op-cert over the AUTHORITATIVE value — the test asserts the signed op-cert's bound\n      `material_fingerprint` equals the authoritative one, NOT the client's doctored value (a client\n      cannot forge a passing verdict).\n- [ ] The signing path materializes the Secrets Manager Ed25519 secret to a **0600 temp file** for\n      the `sshsig.sign` invocation (which requires a file path) and deletes it in a `finally`; a\n      test asserts no key file remains after signing.\n- [ ] The AWS IaC (`infra/`) declares: (a) endpoint authentication via AWS IAM SigV4 (at API\n      Gateway) restricted to a named admin role over TLS; (b) least-privilege IAM for the\n      signing-secret read + repo read; (c) the Ed25519 signing key in AWS Secrets Manager\n      (KMS-CMK-encrypted at rest), server-side SSHSIG signing — NOT AWS KMS managed signing; and\n      (d) a container image whose Dockerfile installs OpenSSH ≥ 8.9. A test asserts the IaC files\n      declare these (Secrets Manager + the SigV4/IAM authorizer + the OpenSSH-bearing container\n      image, and NO `kms:Sign`/managed-signing on the Ed25519 key).\n- [ ] The default local path stays offline (stdio `rebar-mcp`) and never wedges an op (test).\n- [ ] [operator-attested] The trusted server is deployed to AWS from `infra/` and its endpoint\n      answers an authenticated admin request — evidence: a comment recording the deploy (stack/change\n      id or console URL) + a successful authenticated round-trip. (Cloud provisioning is operator\n      work; the IaC declaration + handler above are codebase-verifiable.)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783991773770705001,"uuid":"d8ab4247-4759-4c65-93f4-e5ec8cd85e77"}